<DOC><DOCNO> AP890711-0210 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0059EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     07-11 0870</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0907</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Chase Manhattan Bank has trimmed its primelending rate a half percentage point to 10.5 percent, and althoughno other major banks immediately followed suit, experts predictedthey would do so soon as interest rates continued dropping.   ``I'll be surprised if we go through the week and some of theother major money center banks didn't enter the fold,'' Robert A.Brusca, chief financial economist for Nikko Securities Co.International, said Monday.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   On the eve of an important court hearing,Paramount Communications Inc. said it would add interest to itshostile $12.2 billion offer for Time Inc. if certain delays preventit from closing the deal.   Paramount said it had amended its offer of $200 per share in cashfor all of Time's stock to provide an interest payment of 9 percentannually if it is unable to close the deal within 60 days after Timeeither agrees or is ordered to refrain from interfering withParamount's efforts to obtain needed cable regulatory approvals.   A scheduled hearing today in Delaware Chancery Court coulddetermine whether Paramount can acquire Time or whether Time cancomplete its own takeover of Warner Communications Inc.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal jury has convicted a Wall Streetbrokerage of an insider trading-related charge in a 1986 stock dealbut acquitted the firm of charges in three other deals and cleared atrader of all counts against him.   The verdict Monday against Marcus Schloss andamp; Co. for dealings withjailed inside trader Ivan F. Boesky's company was the firstconviction of a New York Stock Exchange-registered firm in thegovernment's three-year Wall Street insider trading crackdown.   The firm faces a total fine of $1 million. Sentencing was set forSeptember, on a date to be set later.</TEXT><DATELINE>PLYMOUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   CVN Companies Inc. has agreed to beacquired by the smaller QVC Network Inc. in a deal officials hopewill make the companies more competitive against Home ShoppingNetwork Inc. in the video shopping industry.   The agreement announced Monday, valued at more than $400 millionin cash and stock, is subject to approval by shareholders of bothcompanies as well as federal regulatory approval.</TEXT><DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. loweredits bid for LIN Broadcasting Corp. by about $400 million, citing aNew York court decision that was unfavorable to LIN.   The new offer disclosed Monday reduces to about $5.36 billion,from $5.85 billion, the total value of McCaw's bid for the 90percent of LIN shares it does not own. Both companies are majoroperators of cellular phone services.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady hasspurned a proposal from a top bank regulator to create a newinternational insurance fund that would partially protect banksagainst defaults by Third World debtors.   ``We don't think that is necessary at this point in time,'' Bradysaid in a briefing Monday with reporters before his departure thisweek for an economic summit meeting in Paris.   But Brady did not completely rule out the idea, offered byFederal Deposit Insurance Corp. Chairman L. William Seidman.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Texas' Hunt brothers did the best they could inan ``atmosphere of panic'' after the silver market collapse in 1980,their attorney says, denying at the start of their tax-claim trialthat they had set up ``a colossal sham'' partnership.   However, Internal Revenue Service attorney Deborah Butler toldthe judge Monday that the partnership was created to provide``financial relief to the petitioners at a time when they needed itvery badly'' and was subject to taxes when it was dissolved in 1982.</TEXT><DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Xerox Corp. said its board had approved aleveraged employee stock ownership plan for salaried employees andthe repurchase of roughly 11 percent of the company's common stock.   Xerox said the employee stock ownership plan for 57,000 salariedemployees would be financed in part by forfeited merit raises andthe loss of company contributions to a 401(k) retirement plan.   The company said Monday it will implement the plan by issuing$785 million worth of new series B convertible preferred stock andusing the proceeds to repurchase 11 million of its 103 millionoutstanding common shares.</TEXT><DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Financial markets have stabilizedin response to new austerity measures imposed by President CarlosMenem to reduce 1 million percent annual inflation and a massivebudget deficit.   Economic measures announced Sunday night devalued the nationalcurrency by one-half and increased gasoline prices by as much as 610percent. The plan also envisions cutting back government spending,selling many state-run industries, reducing subsidies and tax breaksfor private companies and enforcing widely ignored tax laws.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market rose Monday amid expectations of furtherdeclines in interest rates. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrialsrose 14.80 to 2,502.66, extending its gain since the start of lastweek to 62.60 points.   The dollar declined against several foreign currencies.   Bond prices rose, nudged upward by sharp declines in prices ofsome key commodities.   Corn, soybean, oat, wheat and oil futures prices all fell.</TEXT></DOC>